A header file does not usually contain the actual code of a library function.
Instead, it contains its declaration (prototype).

""The implementation (the real code) is stored in the C standard library, not in the header file.""

BIG QUESTION: if the header file doesn't include the code and it is stored in the c standard library
               how does it fetches it  (ans in notes 5)


                  ************** Ans ****************


This is an excellent question. Understanding this will help you understand how C programs are actually built.

The key is that compiling and linking are two different steps.

Let's follow your program from start to finish.

Step 1: You write your program
#include <stdio.h>

int main()
{
    printf("Hello");
    return 0;
}

Step 2: The Preprocessor

The preprocessor sees:
#include <stdio.h>

and copies the contents of stdio.h into your source file.

It is almost as if your code became:

// Contents of stdio.h (simplified)

int printf(const char *format, ...);

int main()
{
    printf("Hello");
    return 0;
}


Notice something important:
There is no implementation of printf().
Only its declaration.

Step 3: The Compiler

Now the compiler reads:

int printf(const char *format, ...);

and thinks:

"Okay, printf() exists."

When it reaches

printf("Hello");

it already knows

the return type (int)
the parameter types

So it can check your code for errors.

The compiler then creates an object file.

For example:

main.c
    ↓
Compiler
    ↓
main.o

At this point, your program still doesn't contain printf().

Instead, the object file says something like:

I need a function named printf.
Step 4: The Linker (The Important Part)

Now the linker starts.

It sees

main.o

and notices:

printf()

is missing.

So it searches the C Standard Library.

main.o
      │
      ▼
Needs printf()

      │
      ▼
Search standard library

      │
      ▼
Found printf()

      │
      ▼
Link it into the executable

Now your executable contains everything it needs.

main.exe


/**** Where is the Standard Library? ***/

When you install a compiler like GCC, Clang, or MSVC, it comes with libraries.

For example, GCC includes libraries such as:

libc.a
libc.so

or on Windows

msvcrt.dll
ucrtbase.dll

These contain the actual machine code for functions like

printf()
scanf()
malloc()
free()
Complete Build Process
Your Source Code
(main.c)

        │
        ▼

Preprocessor
Copies stdio.h

        │
        ▼

Compiler
Creates main.o

        │
        ▼

Linker
Looks for printf()

        │
        ▼

C Standard Library

        │
        ▼

Executable
(main.exe)
Real-life Analogy

Imagine you're writing a report.

You write:

See Appendix A.

The appendix isn't inside the page you're writing.

It exists elsewhere.

When the final book is assembled, the publisher adds Appendix A.

Your report
      │
      ▼
"See Appendix A"

      │
      ▼
Publisher attaches Appendix A

      │
      ▼
Complete book

Here:

Header file = Table of contents / index ("Appendix A exists")
Standard library = The actual appendix
Linker = The publisher assembling the final book


Q) Why not put the whole printf() code in stdio.h?

Imagine every program included the entire implementation of printf() in the header.

Then every source file would contain thousands of extra lines.

For example:

main.c
+ printf implementation
+ scanf implementation
+ fopen implementation
+ fclose implementation
+ ...

Every .c file would become enormous, compilation would be slower, and
maintaining the library would be much harder.

Instead:

Header (.h) → declares what exists.
Library (.a, .so, .dll) → contains the actual compiled code.

This separation is one of the reasons C scales well to large projects.

